    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Crossing Bridges In Workplace Ethics</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dianne K Olsen discusses Feb 18 The Right Thing article concerning appropriate use of personal ethics in business situations</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Yes, one's ethics or values can  sometimes be at odds with those of the corporation. But sometimes, corporate decisions are just outright unethical.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Yes, one's ethics or values can  sometimes be at odds with those of the corporation. But sometimes, corporate decisions are just outright unethical.</p>
        <p>In those cases, doesn't the ethical employee have a right and an obligation to say where she stands? It may not come to ''if you don't change, I quit,'' but management should offer as much compromise to employees as they ask from employees. It seems to me that an employee who feels that her ethical standards could be breached could ask for assignment to another project. If an employee feels she could be in legal jeopardy, she should be able to move outside the risk area -- even if she doesn't have the opportunity to change the company's behavior.</p>
        <p>DIANNE K. OLSEN  Poughkeepsie, N.Y., Feb. 21</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
